00:09:56.820 --> 00:10:03.780
technical results to non-technical audiences? And by non-technical meaning like non-coding or

00:10:03.780 --> 00:10:11.619
non-statistician? Yeah. So I would say it's probably key to think of pretty much every audience as a

00:10:11.619 --> 00:10:17.140
non-technical audience. Even when you have people who are technical, it's best not to assume that

00:10:17.140 --> 00:10:22.580
they ever know the things that you know, because, you know, it's unlikely that anyone will be as

00:10:22.580 --> 00:10:29.859
deeply immersed in a problem as you are. And in some sense, it can almost be worse if you have a

00:10:29.859 --> 00:10:33.619
technical person and you're like, well, why don't you understand this? Because then they may, you

00:10:33.619 --> 00:10:40.419
know, may feel a little bit hurt by that. But I would say it can be hard. But the biggest thing

00:10:40.419 --> 00:10:48.739
is focusing on the impact of the output first. So I like to tell my team that, you know, people,

00:10:48.739 --> 00:10:54.020
what you might think is like a smallest piece of work is something that someone else is going to

00:10:54.020 --> 00:11:00.739
think is sort of magic. Like, just telling someone earlier today, you know, they're talking about all

00:11:00.739 --> 00:11:04.260
the coding stuff they had done. And I'm like, you know, the thing that's going to really impress

00:11:04.260 --> 00:11:09.780
people is that you just generated this automated piece of documentation from your code, basically

00:11:09.780 --> 00:11:16.580
for free, it took you five minutes. But that's like the magic piece. I remember someone at the

00:11:16.580 --> 00:11:24.179
RStudio conference talking about like, minimizing time to magic. And that kind of thing is what

00:11:24.179 --> 00:11:31.700
really is like the impact driver for most people. So really focusing on the impact in regular words,

00:11:31.700 --> 00:11:37.299
removing the jargon, that kind of thing. And then, you know, trusting yourself that you've done

00:11:37.299 --> 00:11:42.260
all the checking, the assumptions, the really technical details, and, you know, writing that

00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:47.460
down for yourself and having, you know, maybe a good appendix or technical paper to go with your

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:53.460
work. But really, that is the key, I think, for the non-technical audiences. And then,

00:11:54.340 --> 00:11:59.940
sometimes having the, you know, people that are non-technical ask you questions that you just

00:11:59.940 --> 00:12:06.739
didn't even think about, that are really very helpful in sort of being proactive in future

00:12:06.739 --> 00:12:12.260
analysis. So I would say, look at it as an opportunity to like, practice your translation

00:12:12.260 --> 00:12:16.580
skills, even if it's, you know, they're not going to understand your world, you're not necessarily

00:12:16.580 --> 00:12:22.739
going to understand theirs. But especially for decision makers, managers, you know, bottom lines

00:12:22.739 --> 00:12:26.739
are important, right? How does this, how does this save us time? How does this save us money?

00:12:27.700 --> 00:12:32.099
Those are kind of key concepts that I would keep in mind for non-technical spaces.

