and they would give me maybe more than I paid for it. You know, partially just because supplies

00:22:21.459 --> 00:22:29.699
have been so short in nature. But yeah, I think there's just a lot of very different things going

00:22:29.699 --> 00:22:34.420
into, you know, how banks are reacting. Certainly there are, you know, some of the government

00:22:34.420 --> 00:22:43.140
programs, the banks had to help with the funding and like the PPP program, Paycheck Protection

00:22:43.140 --> 00:22:50.420
Program. So that resulted in some interesting data, which I can't say too much specifically

00:22:50.420 --> 00:22:57.540
about the data. But yeah, those are maybe some interesting anomalies that I've seen.

00:22:58.420 --> 00:22:59.619
Awesome. Thank you.

00:23:01.300 --> 00:23:06.979
Thanks, Lindsay. I see Sam asked the question, is your team using Shiny today?

00:23:07.540 --> 00:23:14.660
We do use Shiny. So actually, I have a an interesting story about how we started using Shiny.

00:23:14.660 --> 00:23:23.619
So I think in about, you know, in 2020, when we're, you know, all working from home, and we're

00:23:23.619 --> 00:23:29.060
sort of running, running a crazy amount of stuff, just to better understand, you know, the early

00:23:29.699 --> 00:23:38.420
impacts of the COVID pandemic, basically, because our timeframe, when we really run the stress test

00:23:38.420 --> 00:23:44.579
is basically April through June. And so, you know, the lockdown period really occurred

00:23:44.579 --> 00:23:50.739
essentially in March. And I don't know that any of us really expected it to be what it became. But

00:23:51.939 --> 00:23:57.699
we knew that we'd need to maybe do more analysis than normal, given the situation.

00:23:57.939 --> 00:24:02.979
And I think a lot of us, you know, there were tools in this case, in Excel, in other,

00:24:04.020 --> 00:24:10.500
in other spaces, for these sort of key analytics. And a group of us were just like,

00:24:11.140 --> 00:24:15.300
we just can't deal with this. We can't, we can't like make constant updates to these Excel

00:24:15.300 --> 00:24:22.500
spreadsheets. And so basically, we got kind of a little bit of white space for a couple weeks.

00:24:23.459 --> 00:24:29.219
And I think three or four of us just sat down and said, let's just try to build these things out

00:24:29.219 --> 00:24:37.939
as shiny tools. We had, we had some access to deployment in RStudio Connect. And so we're like,

00:24:37.939 --> 00:24:44.900
let's just try this out. And also, like, we built out some frameworks using just like HTML

00:24:45.380 --> 00:24:52.739
reporting from our markdown. And, you know, we put together what's probably the basis of the set

00:24:52.739 --> 00:24:58.739
of analytics that that we still utilize. And so some of those are shiny, some of those are

00:24:59.859 --> 00:25:05.699
still in HTML from our markdown files. But, you know, like, I think there was a talk actually in

00:25:05.699 --> 00:25:13.859
2020, that inspired me to do the shift things to HTML. And then like that the next step is very

00:25:13.859 --> 00:25:19.459
easy to convert something like that to shiny once you sort of have the framework laid out in

00:25:19.459 --> 00:25:25.780
our markdown. And so there are, it's actually something we have an intern working on right now,

00:25:25.780 --> 00:25:32.180
is to convert some things that are sort of HTML into shiny. So we, we are able to use shiny,

00:25:32.180 --> 00:25:38.020
we're not able to convince everyone to use shiny. But then we're not, we're not trying to be too

00:25:38.020 --> 00:25:46.339
specific with folks who haven't maybe taken the time to get used to the shiny syntax. So we're

00:25:46.339 --> 00:25:53.780
supportive of other tools, Tableau, etc, that people want to use for these sort of analytics.

00:25:53.780 --> 00:25:59.380
But I think our team is, especially those who went to our studio are very excited about shiny.

00:26:00.180 --> 00:26:04.660
And even, even those that are outside our team, we told them about shiny for Python,

00:26:04.660 --> 00:26:06.579
and they're, they're pretty jacked about that, too.

00:26:09.780 --> 00:26:15.699
Cool, thank you. I, because you just mentioned your intern working on that shiny app, too,

00:26:15.699 --> 00:26:20.979
I see Mike, you had a question, question on interns working there. Do you want to jump in?

00:26:24.020 --> 00:26:30.819
Hi, yeah. Nice to see you. I'm Mike Smith at Pfizer. I was just interested to know,

00:26:30.819 --> 00:26:36.180
how are you seeing interns at the minute? You know, how are they coming in? What are their

00:26:36.180 --> 00:26:44.819
levels of knowledge on Python and R and data science tooling? I, I guess my feeling is that

00:26:44.819 --> 00:26:52.099
there would be a whole lot smarter than they were five years ago, or 10 years ago, maybe, or at least

00:26:52.099 --> 00:27:04.180
Yeah, so we, we have had some great luck with interns. We, we've had a program in the last

00:27:04.180 --> 00:27:10.579
couple years start up in Minneapolis, where we do graduate students, we call it a data science

00:27:10.579 --> 00:27:17.300
internship. And their skills have been pretty fantastic. I mean, in some cases, you know,

00:27:17.300 --> 00:27:25.060
they're even more cutting edge with, with these R tools, or Python tools than we are ourselves,

00:27:25.060 --> 00:27:29.699
as you know, folks who maybe haven't been in school for a little while, or haven't had as much

00:27:29.699 --> 00:27:36.579
of the dedicated time to study. So like I said, it, it's been very easy to set them off doing

00:27:36.579 --> 00:27:42.260
things like, hey, go build, go work on building the shiny app, or, hey, like, why don't we figure

00:27:42.260 --> 00:27:48.099
out how to turn this into a package? Like, let's work out what is the right, you know, what is the

00:27:48.099 --> 00:27:53.780
minimum documentation, we want to put in this, and sort of developing, like, how do we actually

00:27:53.780 --> 00:27:58.500
build this in the, in the framework that we have, or deploy it in the framework that we have.

00:27:59.459 --> 00:28:06.099
So they've been great. And I mean, we, we do, in our interview process, you know, we do have sort

00:28:06.099 --> 00:28:12.339
of a code sample, just to make sure that it, you know, does appear that there is some skill in that

00:28:12.339 --> 00:28:18.500
area. But we do also, you know, we're pretty open, because like the idea is for them to learn on the

00:28:18.500 --> 00:28:26.339
job as well. But I think all of the interns that I've worked with have all had very good R skills.

00:28:26.339 --> 00:28:31.540
And I think, at least some Python skills too, we've just been maybe prioritizing the R skills

00:28:31.540 --> 00:28:33.939
a little bit more in our, in our pool.

00:28:37.140 --> 00:28:40.500
Thanks. That, that seems to mirror what I'm seeing. There's, there's a lot of,

00:28:42.099 --> 00:28:44.819
it's almost like the interns could teach us a lot, you know.

00:28:44.819 --> 00:28:48.020
Yes. No, we do. We make them do that, actually, too.

00:28:51.939 --> 00:28:55.699
There was an anonymous question at the beginning, which actually ties in

00:28:55.699 --> 00:28:59.140
to this as well. But when you have people using multiple

00:28:59.140 --> 00:29:05.140
programming languages, so R, Python, SAS, how do you structure the work, and who does what?

00:29:06.739 --> 00:29:08.020
And how do they work together?

00:29:10.099 --> 00:29:17.140
Sure. So I think we have sort of specific tools that we like to use for specific purposes.

00:29:18.020 --> 00:29:24.500
So we'll say we use R as probably our main language, but the, the developers that we work

00:29:24.500 --> 00:29:30.500
with, they might use any tool. So they might use SAS, or Stata, or MATLAB, or some other tool,

00:29:30.500 --> 00:29:40.739
or even R, basically. And so, you know, a lot of us have sort of the multilingual background,

00:29:40.739 --> 00:29:47.859
where maybe we weren't coders in SAS, or Stata, or something else, but in the process of helping

00:29:47.859 --> 00:29:54.739
to translate that code into sort of a production environment, we definitely learn on the fly,

00:29:55.540 --> 00:30:01.380
you know, how to, how to Google the right things for SAS or Stata, or how to interpret, you know,

00:30:01.380 --> 00:30:05.859
what things are happening, you know, because sometimes, like, the algorithms aren't the same.

00:30:06.420 --> 00:30:11.939
When you have to translate something, you have to kind of determine, you know, how much of that

00:30:11.939 --> 00:30:16.739
do you need to dig into versus just say, like, both concepts, conceptually, these are both the

00:30:16.739 --> 00:30:22.739
same thing. But SAS does it different than R, something like that. So I think we did have,

00:30:24.020 --> 00:30:28.900
you know, team members with some familiarity in those spaces, just for some who've worked in

00:30:28.900 --> 00:30:34.020
economics or finance longer, they've definitely not necessarily always been able to use R as their

00:30:34.020 --> 00:30:41.380
first language. So, like, at my time, before joining the Fed, I'd used some SAS in my, my first

00:30:41.380 --> 00:30:46.579
job in finance. So I had a decent background there, I had a decent background in some MATLAB.

00:30:47.619 --> 00:30:53.459
And especially my work in validation, I got to see all of those things, even though I wasn't

00:30:53.459 --> 00:31:00.420
necessarily coding in them regularly. So I think we've sort of highlighted that it's useful to be

00:31:00.420 --> 00:31:08.260
multilingual. But because that helps you to translate things better, or to, you know,

00:31:08.260 --> 00:31:13.300
design them better, maybe than they were in some of those, you know, there are some limitations to

00:31:13.300 --> 00:31:19.459
certain languages, there are limitations to R, but, you know, to understand how it how it works

00:31:19.459 --> 00:31:27.300
more efficiently, in each language can be helpful in the process. So, but we do, I think we more or

00:31:27.300 --> 00:31:33.140
less match people up more based on maybe their financial background versus necessarily their

00:31:33.140 --> 00:31:41.140
software background. Just because we're all translating to R, for the most part, and the

00:31:41.140 --> 00:31:47.459
Python pieces that we have are a little more general. And so we just have a couple folks on

00:31:47.459 --> 00:31:53.219
our team who are a bit more expert in Python, but they still also are expert in R as well.

00:31:56.020 --> 00:32:00.900
Thank you. And I just wanted to mention to everyone too, if there's a particular question

00:32:00.900 --> 00:32:05.939
you want to like, ask a follow up on, or you want to share insights into as well, feel free to just

00:32:05.939 --> 00:32:11.380
raise your hand on, on zoom as well. And then I'll just, I'll just know that you want to jump in.

00:32:13.619 --> 00:32:18.979
But I see as well, there was a anonymous question earlier that was,

00:32:18.979 --> 00:32:24.819
how does your team think about ethics in your work when it comes to things like race or ethnicity?

00:32:24.819 --> 00:32:36.660
Yeah, that's a good question. We, you know, I will say that we thought, maybe I'll separate

00:32:36.660 --> 00:32:43.060
ethics from sort of maybe the diversity equity inclusion. You know, one of our main goals,

00:32:43.060 --> 00:32:50.739
and especially for me as like a hiring manager is to really thoroughly have, have a pool

00:32:50.739 --> 00:32:57.459
every time that we have a posting that meets some specific diversity criteria, but also

00:32:59.140 --> 00:33:03.939
maybe meet some diversity criteria of like diversity of thought or diversity of background

00:33:04.819 --> 00:33:10.660
versus just maybe like typical metrics. And so that means that our hiring process can sometimes

00:33:10.660 --> 00:33:17.699
take a little bit longer. But it also means we don't just hire the first maybe qualified person

00:33:18.660 --> 00:33:24.180
that we come across in our pool. And I think internally, once we have people

00:33:24.180 --> 00:33:29.219
into the organization, we really want to retain them. And so a lot of the focus

00:33:30.739 --> 00:33:36.979
within our organization are to have employee resource networks that cover sort of, you know,

00:33:36.979 --> 00:33:44.420
different intersectional parts of our personalities and work lives. So something for women or,

00:33:44.420 --> 00:33:52.099
you know, allyship for for a lot of different spaces. And then within my team, it's actually

00:33:52.099 --> 00:34:00.660
great, we have a, we sort of do an internal team meeting, where we'll usually discuss,

00:34:01.300 --> 00:34:07.619
you know, topics that sort of overlap in this DEI space, a lot of times from a research perspective.

00:34:07.619 --> 00:34:11.780
So we've covered things like, I don't know, we looked at like the Iceland four day work week,

00:34:12.739 --> 00:34:19.060
they had some studies on that not too long ago, or we look at, you know, what's it been like to go

00:34:19.060 --> 00:34:24.820
back to the office, because our company has gone back to sort of a hybrid mode, and what would

00:34:24.820 --> 00:34:30.820
make that more effective for us? And how has that changed maybe things in your personal life?

00:34:32.260 --> 00:34:39.060
So I think it's always, you know, the goal is that it's just part of the work. And that it's

00:34:39.060 --> 00:34:45.459
not like a separate thing. It's not like we're doing DEI now, and then we go back to our day job.

00:34:45.459 --> 00:34:52.419
No, it's meant to be integrated with within our day job, just to help, you know, help everyone

00:34:52.419 --> 00:34:58.739
realize that these things are always there. We've also had some really fantastic anti racism

00:34:58.739 --> 00:35:05.620
training and those kinds of things within our organization. But then I think when it comes to

00:35:06.179 --> 00:35:13.780
like approaching the work, like on the, you know, modeling side, definitely we're considering,

00:35:13.780 --> 00:35:18.260
you know, what's in the data and what's missing from the data, right? No data is perfect.

00:35:19.699 --> 00:35:25.699
You know, we're, we're relying on banks to provide data that we asked them for based on certain

00:35:25.699 --> 00:35:32.500
instructions. And so understanding, you know, what's missing from that data is really critical

00:35:33.139 --> 00:35:42.739
to thinking about, you know, sort of like, DNI issues. And then, you know, from an ethics

00:35:42.739 --> 00:35:48.979
standpoint, more just like the, the Fed has a very high code of ethics. There are some very

00:35:48.979 --> 00:35:58.260
specific things that were required to avoid or comply with. And I think definitely some things

00:35:58.260 --> 00:36:04.820
about, you know, trading stocks, and even cryptocurrency for some folks are highly

00:36:04.820 --> 00:36:11.699
restricted. But I think we do hold ourselves to, you know, as high of a standard as we can even

00:36:11.699 --> 00:36:16.899
outside of that sort of ethical code of conduct that we have internally.

00:36:19.459 --> 00:36:25.699
Thanks, Lindsay. I see Jonathan had asked in the chat and said just for me to read it out loud.

00:36:26.419 --> 00:36:32.739
But it was, what platforms and fun data set projects did you use to learn or enhance your

00:36:32.739 --> 00:36:41.060
R programming skills in your free time? Yeah, so I think there was a conference,

00:36:41.860 --> 00:36:46.820
maybe that I attended probably like five years ago, a Women in Statistics and Data Science

00:36:46.820 --> 00:36:55.139
Conference. And that was like the first place I'd learned about R-Ladies. And I think, you know,

00:36:55.860 --> 00:37:00.820
one other person from the Minneapolis area who attended with me, she was really inspired and

00:37:00.820 --> 00:37:06.580
decided like, take it on and start up our local chapter again, which had been a little bit defunct

00:37:06.580 --> 00:37:13.540
for a while. And I think just going to some of those meetups is where I was really inspired to

00:37:13.540 --> 00:37:20.419
learn like the tidyverse. You know, it's very safe space, like it can, I think we had some great

00:37:20.419 --> 00:37:26.419
contributors who were able to give good, just really beginner overviews of some of these topics.

00:37:26.419 --> 00:37:33.139
And then, you know, we've had pretty consistent, although we've taken a little bit of a summer

00:37:33.139 --> 00:37:39.699
break, but pretty consistent talks and always learn something in R-Ladies. So that's been a

00:37:39.699 --> 00:37:46.340
really useful way for me to do things. You know, just to use those sort of materials that people

00:37:46.340 --> 00:37:53.860
put together in the course of those kinds of meetups. You know, I've also enjoyed just like

00:37:53.860 --> 00:37:59.860
the Twitter community around RStats. So I don't always, I feel like I kind of know what's going

00:37:59.860 --> 00:38:05.860
on, even if I don't always like dive into something, but like the emergence of this penguins

00:38:05.860 --> 00:38:13.620
data set, like in every example, I've been sort of following that recently. And it was even like

00:38:13.620 --> 00:38:21.860
a highlight of the sort of OpenScapes Cordo talk, which I thought was very, very cool. And I think

00:38:21.860 --> 00:38:30.100
just, you know, trying to immerse myself a little bit more into the community. But, you know, sometimes,

00:38:30.100 --> 00:38:34.100
you know, if I just want to learn a package or something like that, I'll just kind of dive into

00:38:34.100 --> 00:38:41.459
the page documentation. Usually people put pretty good little data examples. I've also had some good

00:38:41.459 --> 00:38:48.580
luck taking, you know, Coursera's that have good kind of R examples as the basis for maybe learning

00:38:48.580 --> 00:38:55.699
a new topic. But yeah, it's just great that there's so much free material, you know, the book down

00:38:56.580 --> 00:39:04.179
package has made it possible that almost everyone publishes their books now on open source,

00:39:04.179 --> 00:39:09.379
basically, if you don't want to get the hard copy. And so I think just, you know, copying and pasting

00:39:09.379 --> 00:39:16.419
from Stack Overflow can sometimes be the first step in any good learning data analysis project.

00:39:18.500 --> 00:39:24.260
Absolutely. And I shared some upcoming R-Ladies meetups and then R user groups

00:39:24.260 --> 00:39:28.979
in the chat as well. When you sort through them like that on meetup, you can see all of them

00:39:28.979 --> 00:39:37.139
all over the world. But I also wanted to ask everybody in the chat to on that topic of like,

00:39:37.139 --> 00:39:42.419
I know you mentioned the Penguin data set, but does anybody have like certain data sets that you

00:39:42.419 --> 00:39:49.860
use for like business examples? Like if you were making the case to your leadership, I've been

00:39:49.860 --> 00:39:57.620
looking for just like good play data sets that are like real business example. If you wouldn't

00:39:57.620 --> 00:40:07.459
mind sharing those in the chat, that would be awesome. I see there are lots of other questions

00:40:07.459 --> 00:40:12.020
from earlier. Let me go up here. Actually, Michael, you had your hand raised. Do you want to jump in?

00:40:13.459 --> 00:40:17.939
Sure, I can jump in. Hi, Lindsay. I'm at the data science consulting firm,

00:40:17.939 --> 00:40:22.899
Ketchbook Analytics, and we work with a ton of banks and lending institutions. So this is

00:40:22.899 --> 00:40:29.219
really right up my alley. I appreciate you coming on here today. My question for you was,

00:40:29.219 --> 00:40:35.219
with stress testing in particular, which is an area that we work in quite a bit in developing

00:40:35.219 --> 00:40:42.419
those models, having some trouble lately with the sort of new approaches that we have and new tools

00:40:42.419 --> 00:40:47.540
that we have for Bayesian modeling that allow us to give more of a probabilistic output, which sort

00:40:47.540 --> 00:40:54.580
of feels more like a stress testing-y type place to have those models as opposed to deterministic

00:40:54.580 --> 00:40:58.659
models that just say, hey, this is exactly what's going to happen next year. Here's your point

00:40:58.659 --> 00:41:06.500
estimate. I've had mixed experience sort of getting buy-in for Bayesian models. I don't know if you

00:41:06.500 --> 00:41:15.300
use any Bayesian methods in your work at all, and if so, do you have any words of wisdom for getting

00:41:15.300 --> 00:41:25.860
buy-in on those? Yeah, so I would say I don't use any specifically right now, but what I like to say

00:41:25.860 --> 00:41:32.020
maybe as a selling point for Bayesian models that maybe people don't think about because a lot of

00:41:32.020 --> 00:41:37.699
people are used to frequentists or likelihood or just maybe haven't had a course in Bayesian

00:41:37.699 --> 00:41:44.580
approaches, and this is something that my partner told me once, is that Bayesians are just much more

00:41:44.580 --> 00:41:51.300
explicit about the assumptions that are present in their models. So sometimes I think we think

00:41:51.300 --> 00:41:56.979
we're getting things for free when we fit frequentist-style models or likelihood-based methods,

00:41:58.739 --> 00:42:03.620
and people can be uncomfortable with the idea of like, oh, the prior changed and therefore

00:42:03.620 --> 00:42:11.459
the output changed, and I think, I actually think like the, you know, credible intervals

00:42:11.459 --> 00:42:17.540
being like an actual probability, having an actual probabilistic interpretation is much

00:42:17.540 --> 00:42:21.459
stronger than sort of the idea of confidence intervals, but a lot of people just don't,

00:42:22.179 --> 00:42:29.620
they don't understand maybe the subtle differences. So I think, you know, what also

00:42:29.620 --> 00:42:34.179
people could be afraid of in Bayesian models sometimes is the, you know, how long does it take

00:42:34.179 --> 00:42:39.780
to actually run this kind of situation, which I think there are a lot of tools now that, you know,

00:42:40.340 --> 00:42:47.219
can allow you to take, you know, much shorter paths to get to an answer, but I would just say that

00:42:47.219 --> 00:42:54.899
like it maybe can be great in certain cases, like where you have very little data and you really

00:42:54.899 --> 00:43:00.979
have to make an assumption, right? So I like to, I don't know, I think I like to think about like

00:43:00.979 --> 00:43:06.899
maybe HR cases where you're trying to determine are we meeting sort of our diversity goals, but

00:43:06.899 --> 00:43:13.060
there are only like five people in this group, right? Can we really make a good assessment using

00:43:13.060 --> 00:43:18.820
like a frequentist analysis to say like, well, one out of the five people, you know, so we're at 20%,

00:43:19.699 --> 00:43:25.060
but in that case, it could be useful to think about like, well, what's a Bayesian approach to

00:43:25.060 --> 00:43:30.260
this, which is that like maybe we make some assumption that we're either hitting our criteria

00:43:30.260 --> 00:43:36.739
or not hitting our criteria, and then let the data do a little bit of informing of that, you

00:43:36.739 --> 00:43:42.419
know, updating of that assumption. You know, I think if you have, you have a huge amount of data,

00:43:44.020 --> 00:43:49.620
you know, theory says that the basically the Bayesian approach and the likelihood approach are

00:43:49.620 --> 00:43:56.580
essentially the same in those cases. So that's maybe not the case where you'd want to make your

00:43:56.580 --> 00:44:03.780
sort of argument, but certainly in the small data cases, or I think there are definitely tools for

00:44:03.780 --> 00:44:08.179
different kinds of time series, or I've been reading a little bit about this like Google

00:44:08.179 --> 00:44:14.820
time series method that relies on Bayesian stuff, or Bayesian like, you know, model selection

00:44:14.820 --> 00:44:21.060
criterions that, you know, there's definitely ways to make arguments about perhaps how much better

00:44:21.060 --> 00:44:27.620
those methods do just from a prediction performance. So maybe it's more too about like what

00:44:27.620 --> 00:44:32.899
are the metrics people really care about, and can you hit those better with the Bayesian model than

00:44:32.899 --> 00:44:39.860
perhaps like a frequentist model? Awesome, I appreciate it. Thank you. Do you have any

