00:45:09.780 --> 00:45:14.020
when it isn't appropriate, and obviously if you have plenty of data, you know, you shouldn't need

00:45:14.020 --> 00:45:20.100
to employ a Bayesian model, but we see some portions of credit portfolios, some segments of

00:45:20.100 --> 00:45:24.580
those portfolios that have never had a default event. So if someone's trying to predict probability

00:45:24.580 --> 00:45:28.899
of default, take a frequentist approach, it's going to be zero, but there's not, there's not

00:45:28.899 --> 00:45:34.500
really a zero percent chance that, you know, no loan in that segment of the portfolio will ever

00:45:34.500 --> 00:45:38.820
default. So that's, that's sort of where I think priors can help quite a bit. Definitely.

